# Security Checklist

Apply before committing code that handles user input, authentication, API endpoints, or sensitive data.

## Pre-Commit Checks

- [ ] No hardcoded secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens, connection strings) in source
- [ ] All user input validated with Zod schemas at system boundaries
- [ ] Database queries use Prisma (parameterized) — never raw string interpolation
- [ ] Auth checked on every protected API route (use `getServerSession(authOptions)`)
- [ ] Error responses do not leak internal details (stack traces, SQL errors, file paths)
- [ ] Rate-sensitive endpoints have throttling or abuse prevention
- [ ] No `console.log` of sensitive data (tokens, passwords, PII, session objects)

## OWASP Patterns for Next.js + Prisma

| Threat | Prevention |
|---|---|
| Injection | Prisma parameterizes queries by default; never use `$queryRawUnsafe` with user input |
| Broken Auth | Validate session server-side via `getServerSession(authOptions)`; never trust client cookies alone |
| Sensitive Data Exposure | Keep `NEXTAUTH_SECRET`, `DATABASE_URL`, API keys in env vars only; use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix only for truly public values |
| XSS | React escapes by default; never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with user content without DOMPurify |
| CSRF | Next.js API routes + NextAuth CSRF tokens; verify origin on state-changing endpoints |
| Broken Access Control | Check user ownership before returning/modifying resources (e.g., `where: { userId: session.user.id }`) |

## Secret Detection Patterns

Flag immediately if found in source files:

```
sk-...          (OpenAI keys)
ghp_...         (GitHub tokens)
AKIA...         (AWS keys)
password = "..."
token = "..."
apiKey = "..."
```

## Prisma-Specific

- Always use `select` to return only needed fields — never return password hashes or internal IDs to clients
- Use `prisma.$transaction()` for multi-table operations that must be atomic
- Add `@unique` constraints in the schema before relying on uniqueness in application code
